<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 94 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Turning to time-share
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Eight years ago, I bought a freehold house in France. I now wish to convert
it into a time-share, with six individuals each taking one-sixth of the
property for Pounds 10,000 each. Should the legalities be arranged in
Britain or France? And what exactly are the tax implications?
France. After all, it was in that country's alpine resorts that time-share
began in the 1960s, so a French property lawyer should be able to guide you.
We assume you are a UK resident; thus, capital gains liabilities may arise
in the transfer to the time-share company. The Inland Revenue publications
department at Somerset House, London WC2 (tel: 071-438 6420) will be able to
supply you with an appropriate booklet. (Murray Johnstone).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
