<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US jobs data fail to motivate
Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
After holding their own for most of the day in the wake of a broadly
encouraging October employment report, US share prices dropped sharply in
late trading as bond yields climbed to their highest levels in more than
three years, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 38.36 at 3,807.52.
The more broadly-based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended down 5.63 at 462.28,
while the American Stock Exchange composite finished 1.66 lower at 452.91
and the Nasdaq composite down 6.02 at 766.08. Trading volume on the NYSE was
283m shares.
The market opened in an uncertain mood after the eagerly-awaited October
jobs figures proved a mixed bag for equity investors. The good news was that
the labour market continued to grow last month, but not so strongly as to
raise fears of resurgent inflation. The Labor department reported that
non-farm payrolls increased by 194,000 in October, well below most Wall
Street forecasts. The national unemployment rate, meanwhile, fell
unexpectedly from 5.9 per cent to 5.8 per cent.
Overall, the report was encouraging for stocks. Share prices, however, were
unable to capitalise on the figures because bond prices fell for the fifth
consecutive day. The bond market was upset by particular details within the
jobs report, namely stronger than expected manufacturing employment and wage
levels. As bonds dropped further in the afternoon, pushing the yield on the
benchmark 30-year government issue to a new three year high of 8.16 per
cent, stocks moved lower in tandem and the market closed at its lowest point
of the day after a wave of late program selling.
Among individual stocks, several prominent Dow issues took a beating in late
trading. IBM fell Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 7 5/8 , International Paper lost
Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 71 5/8 , and Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing
slipped Dollars 1 to Dollars 53. Eli Lilly fell Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 62
1/2 after the drugs group announced a deal with the Federal Trade Commission
that will allow Eli Lilly to purchase the drugs distributor PCS. The
company's share price had risen earlier in the week in anticipation of the
agreement. Oil stocks, which were higher earlier this week, ran into
selling, with Exxon falling Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 61 1/2 , Philips
Petroleum Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 34 7/8 and Royal Dutch Petroleum Dollars
1 3/4 to Dollars 111 1/8 .
On the Nasdaq market, Biogen dropped Dollars 2 5/8 to Dollars 38 in volume
of 3.2m shares as investors reacted to the news that the company had been
served with several class-action lawsuits alleging federal securities law
violations in connection with Biogen's plans to shut down activities related
to its Hirulog product.
Canada
Toronto stocks posted solid losses with continued weakness in bonds and the
US dollar. The TSE 300 index dropped 28.19 to 4,198.63 in volume of 52.7m
shares. Thirteen of the 14 sub-indexes were down, led by transportation,
metals, conglomerates and industrial products. Only paper and forest stocks
posted gains, up 0.35 per cent on the day. Venezuela
Caracas dipped another 2 per cent, this time as fund managers studied the
government's new resolution on repatriation of profits, announced five weeks
ago in an attempt to bring foreign investors back into the market, but only
published this week. The fund managers thought that there would be big
problems in implementing the resolution, and the Merinvest composite index
fell 2.84 to 138.84.
</TEXT>
