<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 94 / UK Company News: Starmin deeper in the red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Starmin, the quarry products company chaired by Lord Parkinson which is in
survival talks with its bankers, yesterday announced increased losses for
the first half of 1994 after a series of provisions and exceptional charges.
The pre-tax loss of Pounds 1.69m (Pounds 1.24m) was published after the
market closed. Sales were 19 per cent lower at Pounds 6.96m.
The accounts were prepared on a going concern basis, a status which
accountants Ernst &amp; Young described as fundamentally uncertain given the
negotiations with bankers.
However, Mr Michael Gurner, the chief executive appointed in July at the
behest of Starmin's bankers, said the refinancing talks were going well.
Starmin was considering various ways of raising funds to eliminate its
Pounds 6m debt, such as a placing and open offer.
Toal exceptional charges and provisions came to Pounds 1.5m. Excluding
exceptionals, operating profits from continuing businesses improved from
Pounds 173,000 to Pounds 304,000.
Losses per share deepened to 0.5p (0.4p). Last year Starmin breached banking
covenants when doubled losses of Pounds 23.2m left it with shareholders'
funds of just Pounds 3.42m.
