<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 94 / Dollars 1.6bn Chinese jet order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
McDonnell Douglas Aircraft yesterday signed a Dollars 1.6bn order for 40
medium-sized twin-engine jets from a Chinese delegation during a three-day
trade conference in Washington on telecommunications and transportation. The
order was welcomed by Mr Ron Brown, commerce secretary, as another bit of
good news as the mid-term elections approach. The agreement had originally
provided for all the jets to be made in China, but to meet the rapid growth
in the Chinese aviation market, 20 of them will now be built in the US over
the next four years, raising the value of the order. Engines will be
produced by International Aero Engines in Connecticut. The delegation is
expected to place a number of orders to counter the soaring US bilateral
trade deficit. The Chinese are also pushing their case for China's admission
into the World Trade Organisation as a founding member.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>McDonnell Douglas Aircraft Finance Corp.
    International Aero Engines.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
