<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Using cattle to repair the land
 -The controversial techniques of a Namibian farmer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID SPARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nambia, the driest country in southern Africa, is worried by the loss of
trees, mopane bush and grass in the sandy, heavily-grazed, populous communal
areas of the far north.
Further south it is concerned by the spread of impenetrable thornbush
thickets on commercial farms, which occurs because browsing game animals are
fewer in number and loss of grass around waterpoints gives the bush a
chance.
Argo Rust, who farms near Windhoek Airport, is proposing a controversial
answer to both problems. Cattle, he believes, can cure as well as cause
degradation of arid land.
He has pursued that principle for 25 years and has doubled to 600 the number
of cattle on his small farm. To spread his ideas, which are controversial
with agricultural advisers, he founded the Namibia Centre for Holistic
Resources Management in 1989. It has 65 members.
Success has enabled him to give a better deal to his seven workers. 'If you
want to involve your labour force, they must understand the goal and be part
of it,' he says. 'That can happen only if their quality of life is
addressed.'
In the 1960s he took over the 4,000-hectare family farm, Sonnleiten, which
had only 300 cattle. He was advised to destroy encroaching bush and reduce
the number of cattle.
Instead, he pursued the ideas of a Rhodesian, Alan Savory, who had noticed
that national parks, with their big, constantly moving herds of game, had
good grass.
The problem, says Mr Rust, is not the number of animals but the time they
spend on a piece of land. If this is controlled, the hooves of a big herd
break up the surface and their dung manures it, encouraging grass to grow
and preventing thornbush establishing itself.
He also decided on a holistic approach, avoiding the use of chemicals that
could harm important dung beetles.
Fences are used to divide his land into paddocks around waterpoints. Cattle
stay in each paddock for a limited time. He points out that similar results
could be achieved without fences on communal land by herding cattle from
place to place. He has been surprised to find that grass germinates best in
corridors where cattle tramp most.
Some of his land was like concrete, yet it recovered despite below-average
rain, which suggests even the worst land can be restored.
Researchers have now discovered his land has a higher percentage of
perennial grasses than land farmed conventionally by the agricultural
college next door.
</TEXT>
