<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / International Company News: Acquisitions help TBS to lift
operating profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turner Broadcasting System yesterday reported a 46 per cent improvement in
third-quarter operating profits, to Dollars 88m, on revenues of Dollars
739m, up from Dollars 501m a year ago, in the wake of strong contributions
from recently-acquired units, including the New Line Cinema and Castle Rock
movie production companies.
TBS, however, reported a net loss of Dollars 5m for the period due to
several extraordinary items, including accounting changes and a charge to
cover the retirement of debt.
Mr Ted Turner, chairman of TBS, singled out the performance of the group's
New Line Cinema unit, which produced the hit film Mask, TBS's first film to
gross Dollars 100m in box office revenues. Of the Dollars 234m increase in
entertainment operations revenues to Dollars 542m, Dollars 178m came from
New Line, Castle Rock and the Hanna-Barbera animation unit, all of which
were acquired between late 1993 and early 1994.
TBS's news division, which includes the CNN network, posted an 18 per cent
increase in revenues to Dollars 163.5m. Higher domestic advertising revenues
were boosted by stronger viewer ratings, and subscription revenues increased
16 per cent, primarily because of higher sales in the US satellite dish
market.
The baseball players' strike affected TBS's miscellaneous revenues, which
include earnings from the Atlanta Braves baseball clubs. These fell 39 per
cent to Dollars 37.7m.
TBS's share price climbed Dollars  1/2 to close at Dollars 18 1/8 in New
York yesterday.
</TEXT>
