<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / UK Company News: Out of Africa and into battle
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Nov 27 1917: Born Roland Walter Fuhrhop, in India; educated at Churchers
public school, Petersfield.
1948: Left for Africa.
1961: Invited to run London &amp; Rhodesian Mining &amp; Land Company, became
Lonrho.
1973: Described by Edward Heath as 'the unacceptable face of capitalism.'
1973: Boardroom revolt; Rowland fights dismissal via High Court, becomes
sole MD.
1977-78: Lonrho builds 29.9 per cent stake in House of Fraser; Rowland joins
HoF board.
1981: Lonrho's Pounds 226m bid for HoF blocked by MMC.
1983: DTI investigates shareholdings in HoF.
1984: Lonrho sells its stake to the Fayed brothers, but buys new 6.3 per
cent stake.
1985: Fayeds bid Pounds 615m for HoF.
1987-88: DTI inspectors investigate takeover, report passed to Serious Fraud
Office.
1990: DTI publishes highly critical report, which forms basis for Lonrho's
legal attacks.
1991-92: Bank of England strips Fayeds of control of Harrods Bank;Takeover
Panel censures Fayed brothers.
1993: Fayeds float HoF stores, but not Harrods.
Jan 1993: Dieter Bock becomes Lonrho's biggest shareholder.
Feb 1993: Bock appointed joint chief executive.
May 1993: Observer sold to The Guardian.
Oct 1993: Non-executive directors appointed.
Sep 1994: Rowland wins fight to stay as Lonrho joint CEO.
Nov 1994: Rowland agrees to relinquish executive role.
</TEXT>
