<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / Nolan may probe private funds for political parties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Nolan committee on standards of conduct in public life may investigate
the funding of political parties by private organisations - in spite of the
prime minister's insistence that this should be outside its remit.
Lord Nolan, a leading law lord, yesterday clearly indicated that the
committee, which had its first meeting yesterday, would conduct the widest
possible examination of rules for public servants. He said political
donations would come within his committee's remit. The committee could also
make recommendations on whether MPs should have paid interests outside their
parliamentary work.
He confirmed that the committee would not investigate any of the specific
allegations of 'sleaze' that have been made against members of Mr John
Major's government. But it appeared likely that former cabinet ministers who
accepted paid directorships at companies with which they had been officially
involved would be cross-examined in televised sessions.
Asked whether the funding of political parties would fall within the
committee's remit, Lord Nolan said: 'I would be very surprised if it did
not, in this sense: that if party political funding was associated with some
preference to the person providing the funds, some official preference, some
government preference, then it would plainly come within our terms of
reference.'
This was in contrast to a statement by the prime minister in the Commons
last week that the committee's investigation would have 'nothing to do with
the financing of political parties, which has been dealt with by the Home
Affairs Select Committee'.
On the subject of whether MPs can hold outside interests Lord Nolan said the
committee could not dictate to the Commons what rules it should have. But
the committee would examine submissions from political groups on whether MPs
should be allowed to have any paid outside interests.
The committee has been asked to submit a first report within six months. In
the early stages its work will be divided into four groups. These will
examine the question of gifts in cash or kind to ministers, payments to MPs
for parliamentary services, appointments to quangos, and paid appointments
of recently retired ministers.
</TEXT>
