<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / CBI appeals for reinforcements on the green front: A
catalogue of complaints from business leaders about the cost analysis of
environmental regulations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British businesses are starting to chafe under the weight of environmental
regulation.
They feel the government is creating laws without sufficiently balancing the
costs and benefits. They also wish the government would make up its mind
about environmental issues. These concerns will be reflected in a document
which the Confederation of British Industry will publish at its annual
conference next week.
Many of the points in the report challenge the line taken by government on
environmental issues and are likely to provoke a response from Mr Michael
Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, who will be addressing the
conference.
The CBI says there is little evidence for the government's claim that
environmental legislation makes business more competitive by creating
pressure for greater efficiency. The CBI says this 'has not been justified
by a full analysis of the costs and benefits of legislation across affected
sectors'.
Nor, in the CBI's view, are new environmental initiatives providing 'massive
new opportunities for products and services' along the lines much-touted by
ministers. Where these initiatives go with the grain of the market, they do
help strengthen innovative businesses. But where they do not, they add
unnecessarily to the cost burden.
'At present, too many businesses are falling foul of the pitfalls rather
than seizing the opportunities,' the CBI says.
A further problem is the effect of regulation on international
competitiveness. A quarter of respondents to a CBI poll said they were
experiencing difficulties gaining access to foreign markets, mainly because
of eco-labelling schemes in other countries. Thirty per cent said that they
suffered specific British disadvantages because of standards imposed
domestically, and the stricter enforcement of EU legislation in the UK.
Although the CBI accepts that some businesses may not be responding to
opportunities, it lays much of the blame at the government's door. Among the
criticisms it makes are:
The government does not pay enough attention to the effect that
environmental regulation has on competitiveness. It cites the fact that the
white paper on competitiveness issued earlier this year has only one page on
the environment but 20 pages on education and training.
Government needs to provide a more supportive policy framework where the
benefits outweigh the costs of action by business. Environmental regulators
are not sufficiently sensitive to the costs they impose. The CBI thinks
regulators could take a leaf out of the book of the Health and Safety
Executive, which has a longer record of dealing with business.
The government should create more regulatory certainty by establishing
policy on key issues, particularly who pays for contaminated land.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, said that industry was keen to get
into a 'win-win' situation where well-planned regulation brought benefits to
both business and the environment. 'This is not a report which says 'We
can't afford all this environmental regulation.' But it does reflect
frustration over a lot of wasted effort.'
He thought that there were promising signs in the government's proposal for
a new environmental agency which would draw together the functions of
pollution and water regulators. He welcomed the clause in the draft bill for
the agency which would instruct it to balance the costs and benefits of
regulation.
The CBI document is not entirely about what the government should do,
however. It also lays out an agenda for business. Among its recommendations
are that business should give greater stress to environmental issues in its
board and company policy, and that it should identify the opportunities
created by the environment ahead of regulatory developments.
The FT interview, Page 14
</TEXT>
