<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / Post Office unrepentant over sell-off campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Post Office faces 'crippling uncertainty' after the cabinet's decision
to abandon its privatisation, Mr Michael Heron, Post Office chairman, warned
last night.
He added it was 'in danger of going into decline' without the fast
introduction of the changes the Post Office needed to compete commercially.
Mr Heron - with the backing of the Post Office board - also said that the
nationwide network of post offices and delivery of letters to every address
at a uniform and affordable price would now be 'undoubtedly threatened'.
The board reaffirmed yesterday that it would be pressing 'for the commercial
freedom needed to secure the future of the business'.
The Post Office management is unrepentant about its aggressive public
campaign to secure privatisation. 'We cannot wish our problems away,' said
one senior manager. 'We will now be pressing the government to go as far as
possible to the furthest perimeters of what is permissible to get in private
investment through joint ventures and partnerships.'
Mr Heron said: 'The Post Office needs to escape from a government system of
cash-driven management to gain access to external finance and to develop its
business through whatever commercial means are most appropriate.'
He added that it was crucial that the Post Office must be free to meet 'the
growing competition in the UK and ensure technological change in the
communications world would be an opportunity and not a problem'.
Mr Alan Johnson, general secretary of the UCW postal workers' union, said
the cabinet's climbdown was a vindication of the union's 26-month campaign
of opposition.
He said: 'This is a real victory for the British people. It is heartening
that the overwhelming views of the public have been heard. What we must now
do is work hard to deliver real commercial freedom in an integrated Post
Office while (it is) in the public sector.'
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, said the union's campaign had been
'modern trade-unionism at its best', showing 'the effectiveness of modern
campaigning methods for trade-union causes'.
The National Consumer Council said the decision was 'a victory for
commonsense'. It added: 'We were concerned none of the options considered by
the government would safeguard rural post offices.'
Mr Keith Bill, secretary of the Protecting Postal Services group - a
coalition of 3,090 charities and voluntary organisations - said that 'the
threat of privatisation was a monster that should never have been let
loose'. He added: 'We knew that offices in rural areas would have closed and
services we take for granted would have been eroded despite the assurances
of Mr Heseltine and Post Office management.'
