<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / Modest rise in new mortgages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New net mortgage lending in September was only slightly higher than a year
ago, according to figures published yesterday which further underline the
slowness and fragility of the UK mortgage market recovery.
Bank of England statistics show new net lending totalled Pounds 2.11bn in
September compared with Pounds 2.05bn in the corresponding month last year.
A similar picture emerges from the statistics for loans approved, an
important forward-looking indicator since they translate into lending
undertaken in the following weeks. In September 83,000 loans were approved,
compared with 82,000 in the same month last year. New gross lending was,
however, higher this September than last, standing at Pounds 5.2bn, compared
with Pounds 4.59bn.
The figures also underline how market shares have changed in the total
amounts lent. In September building societies carried out more than 60 per
cent of the new net lending.
Last September, when fixed-rate mortgages offered by banks were particularly
popular, banks and societies both undertook about the same amounts of
lending.
The Council of Mortgage Lenders, which represents banks, societies and
centralised lenders, said levels of mortgage activity were 'only modest' and
reiterated its warnings against 'nasty shocks' for the housing market in the
Budget.
</TEXT>
