<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / 'New Austrian' system is cheaper but more risky
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 'new Austrian' tunnelling method, which is at the centre of a safety
inquiry into the Heathrow tunnel collapse, is not new at all.
The concept championed by Dr Ladislaus von Rabcewicz, a Salzburg consulting
engineer, in the late 1950s and early 1960s, has been used with success
internationally for almost 40 years.
Hundreds of projects have used the method, including the Frankfurt and
Washington metros, the Orange-Fish tunnel which diverts water under Suurberg
Mountain to Eastern Cape Province in South Africa, and a water tunnel
diverting the Indus River for the Tarbela dam in Pakistan.
It was used to carve the world's biggest undersea cavern for a rail
cross-over for the Channel tunnel, 40 metres below the seabed and 5 miles
off the British coast.
The technique requires engineers to use the strength of the rock surrounding
the tunnel to minimise the extra strengthening required to prevent collapse
or catastrophic settlement - as occurred two weeks ago at Heathrow.
Its advantage is that it allows excavation by conventional diggers rather
than expensive tunnel-boring machines, permitting faster construction and
greater design flexibility.
Mr Colin Kirkland, development director of consulting engineers Sir William
Halcrow, and former technical director for Eurotunnel, the Channel tunnel
operator, said that it can be up to 25 per cent cheaper than conventional
tunnelling methods.
Much depends on geology and ground conditions. Underground caverns in the
Alps have supported themselves for centuries. It would be impossible to
construct a fabricated lining which could bear the weight of the kilometres
of rock below an Alpine peak.
Mr Kirkland said that in Italy engineers froze gravel, which normally would
be too unstable and have insufficient strength, to allow them to use the
'new Austrian' method.
The British Health and Safety Executive, which is investigating the Heathrow
collapse, is examining whether the method is suitable for use in London clay
 -even though a Pounds 1.5m test tunnel using the method has suffered no
problems since it was constructed in 1992 by BAA, the airport operator.
Alternatives to the method include the laborious installation of strong
prefabricated tunnel linings as excavation proceeds, or using a
cut-and-cover technique, excavating the ground from the surface, which is
stabilised by massive concrete structures while the tunnel is built.
Because of the unpredictability of ground conditions, which can change
radically in a matter of inches, costly over-engineering invariably occurs.
Dr Myles O'Reilly, former head of the ground engineering division of the
Department of Transport's research laboratory, said that the original
cast-iron linings of the London Underground were eight times stronger than
necessary.
The 'new Austrian' method, which encourages a minimum of additional
strengthening during excavation, is riskier but cheaper. Its success depends
on the precision of engineering predictions of likely ground responses to
excavation and on sophisticated measuring procedures, which should allow
engineers time to strengthen the tunnel if unexpected movement occurs.
In harder ground rock bolts up to 6 metres long might be inserted at points
of weakness. These are then cemented in and tightened to bind the rock
together. A steel mesh is used to cover tunnel walls, which are sprayed with
a quick-drying concrete.
Once a project is sufficiently advanced a final reinforced lining is
installed - as it would be with other methods. The undersea cavern for the
Channel tunnel includes a concrete lining up to a metre thick. Dr O'Reilly
said: 'The risk therefore is during the construction phase. The two new
stations being built under Heathrow by the 'new Austrian' method, for
example will have the same standard of strengthening and reinforcement as
any London Underground station, when completed.'
The risk of damage and loss of life, obviously, is much greater when
construction is taking place in highly populated areas. Three people died in
Munich in September when a bus fell into a hole caused by the collapse of a
tunnel being built using the 'new Austrian' method for the Munich metro.
There have been other failures involving the 'new Austrian' method,
including several significant collapses during the construction of 120km of
tunnels for the 330km long Hannover to Wurzburg high-speed railway line in
Germany. The most spectacular failure occured at Krieberg in 1986, when more
than 55m of a tunnel collapsed, causing massive settlement of the ground
above. The incident could have caused a major disaster if it had occurred
under a big office block.
Mr Kirkland said: 'The method is not inappropriate for London clay but it
does require a high standard of monitoring and construction control if a
project is not to be exposed to unacceptable risk.'
</TEXT>
