<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / Spy chief rejects US-style agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Stella Rimington, the director-general of the security service MI5,
yesterday hit out at the creation of a US-style national counter-terrorist
agency, saying that recent experience had shown that a 'large number of
agencies and organisations can co-operate effectively'.
She said that the ceasefires in Northern Ireland had been brought about by
political progress achieved 'in the context of a wider counter-terrorist
strategy'.
Speaking to police chiefs, Whitehall officials and government lawyers
including Sir Nicholas Lyell, the attorney-general, Mrs Rimington promoted
her agency as an efficient counter-terrorist organisation which had provided
useful advice to the government on political issues such as Northern
Ireland.
Her views are in contrast to some experts and police officers, who have been
critical of the fragmented state of Britain's law enforcement agencies and
have called for a single national organisation similar to the US Federal
Bureau of Investigation.
Her move comes as the future of her agency and others is uncertain because
of budgetary pressures and shifting political priorities. The secret
services are to have their spending, administration and policies scrutinised
by a parliamentary committee for the first time later this year.
Mrs Rimington said that while the Ulster ceasefires were welcome 'after so
many years of violence we must remain cautious'.
She referred to attacks by Middle East terrorists, and said: 'Compared with
the traditional certainties of the cold war era, with its frame of reference
apparently fixed for all time, the service's responsibilities, and the
environment in which we operate, are today all in a state of flux.'
