<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 94 / FT Conferences: Flood cover for London 'set to end'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Insurance bought by many companies against London flood damage may be
withdrawn as part of a trend by insurance companies toward limiting exposure
to some large hazards, a risk specialist said yesterday.
Mr Clive Pracy, head of risk management at London Transport, said that
because of the withdrawal of cover for some risks, the setting of limits on
policies and increasing premiums, buyers of insurance - not the providers -
were taking over the role of risk-taker.
London Transport is worried that a rising water table will increase the cost
of keeping water out of the Underground. 'I less than cheerfully predict -
particularly in my business - that flood risk in London will soon disappear
as an insurable item,' Mr Pracy told a Financial Times conference on
corporate risk management and the international insurance industry.
He said that companies had yet to market insurance policies to fill the gap
created by the ending of unlimited employers' liability cover in the UK from
January 1 next year. Unless companies make special arrangements, most
policies will be capped at Pounds 10m or less of cover.
Mr Herbert Harrell, chairman of Harrell Associates, a US consultancy, told
the conference that 'relationships between corporate buyers and sellers in
the insurance industry are very poor, to the detriment of both sides'.
But he said that part of the fault lay with companies buying insurance
policies. Insurers were not seen as strategic partners in the same way as
investment bankers. 'Risk is seen by senior general management simply as a
cost factor, not as a potential source of competitive advantage,' Mr Harrell
said.
He said that, as well as controlling costs, companies should be concerned to
obtain insurance cover that was denied to competitors, a fast response from
their insurance companies and expert advice in judging and lessening risks.
Mr Walter Kielholz, executive board member at Swiss Reinsurance, said that
the distribution of insurance and reinsurance products was not
cost-efficient.
He said he was 'amazed at the portion of premium that gets lost on its way
from the original risk to the ultimate risk carrier'. The obvious conclusion
was that the 'risk carrier has to get closer to the risk'.
</TEXT>
