FT  04 NOV 94 / Gaz de France pulls out staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French state gas company Gaz de France has withdrawn nearly all 200 of
its expatriate staff from Algeria after Islamic fundamentalists murdered two
foreign drilling experts, the newspaper Le Monde reported yesterday. A Gaz
de France official declined to comment except to say: 'We are still present
in Algeria and gas deliveries continue.'
Le Monde said the decision to pull out Gaz de France expatriates was taken
after the killing of a French and Italian technician employed by a French
company in the Aures mountains of north-east Algeria on October 18. A senior
French military official said last week that Paris was concerned by the
attack, since it could signal an offensive by rebels against Algeria's gas
and oil industries, the country's main currency earners. Gaz de France has
been active in Algeria virtually since independence in 1962.
